04676nam a22008295i 9780814764442DE-B159720220329044247.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220329t20082008nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147644427 a10.18574/nyu/97808147644422doi  a(DE-B1597)548472  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHV7936.C88 M356 2008 7aSOC0040002bisacsh04a363.2502851 aManning, Peter K., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Technology of Policing :bCrime Mapping, Information Technology, and the Rationality of Crime Control /cPeter K. Manning. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2008] 4c©2008  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNew Perspectives in Crime, Deviance, and Law ;v400tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tI. Theorizing -- tII. Case Studies -- tIII. Appraising -- tEpilogue -- tAppendix A: Data and Methods -- tAppendix B: Professional “Faery Tales” and Serious Organizational Ethnography Compared -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWith the rise of surveillance technology in the last decade, police departments now have an array of sophisticated tools for tracking, monitoring, even predicting crime patterns. In particular crime mapping, a technique used by the police to monitor crime by the neighborhoods in their geographic regions, has become a regular and relied-upon feature of policing. Many claim that these technological developments played a role in the crime drop of the 1990s, and yet no study of these techniques and their relationship to everyday police work has been made available.Noted scholar Peter K. Manning spent six years observing three American police departments and two British constabularies in order to determine what effects these kinds of analytic tools have had on modern police management and practices. While modern technology allows the police to combat crime in sophisticated, detail-oriented ways, Manning discovers that police strategies and tactics have not been altogether transformed as perhaps would be expected. In The Technology of Policing, Manning untangles the varying kinds of complex crime-control rhetoric that underlie much of today’s police department discussion and management, and provides valuable insight into which are the most effective-and which may be harmful—in successfully tracking criminal behavior.The Technology of Policing offers a new understanding of the changing world of police departments and information technology’s significant and undeniable influence on crime management.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aCrime analysiszUnited StatesxData processing. 0aCrime preventionzUnited States. 0aDigital mapping. 0aInformation retrievalzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Criminology.2bisacsh  aOffers.  achanging.  acrime.  adepartments.  ainfluence.  ainformation.  amanagement.  apolice.  asignificant.  atechnologys.  aundeniable.  aunderstanding.  aworld.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814764442423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814764442/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK